\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 155.         GLOBULARIACEAE}
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc Edit. V.H. Heywood.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial herbs or small shrubs. Leaves simple, alternate or in rosettes. Flowers 5-merous, zygomorphic, in dense capitula surrounded by an involucre. Corolla usually blue. Stamens 4, rarely 2. Ovary 1-locular; ovule 1, pendent. Fruit dry, enclosed in the persistent calyx.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Literature: O. Schwarz, {\i Bot. Jahrb.}{\b  69}: 318-373 (1938).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 1.            Globularia}                 L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Usually evergreen. Flowers in capitula. Corolla 2-lipped; upper lip usually 2-lobed, often small; lower lip 3-lobed, longer than the upper. Stamens and style exserted; stigma 2-lobed.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   All species grow in dry places such as mountain rocks, grassland or stony slopes.
\par

